\'95
\f2\b Conversation Summary \'97 Paper 3: PINN for Cloud Droplet Profile Retrieval
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Context
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 You're finalizing your dissertation (defense target: June 2026) at LASP/CU Boulder. Papers 1 and 2 used optimal estimation (Gauss-Newton) to retrieve vertical profiles of cloud droplet effective radius from MODIS multispectral reflectances, validated against VOCALS-REx in situ data. Paper 3 will tackle the same problem using physics-informed neural networks.
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Key Problems from Papers 1 & 2 That Motivate Paper 3
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Non-unique solutions:
\f4\b0  Many droplet profiles produce reflectances within MODIS uncertainty (Figs. 8-9 of Paper 1). The Gauss-Newton solver finds local minima.
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Weak cloud base sensitivity:
\f4\b0  Weighting functions at all SWIR wavelengths peak near cloud top; only ~8% of signal at 2.13 \uc0\u956 m comes from the lowest quartile.
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Hard constraints required:
\f4\b0  Without enforcing r_bot < r_top, the solver converges to physically unrealistic states.
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Only 2 vertical levels retrieved:
\f4\b0  The state vector was x = (r_top, r_bot, \uc0\u964 _c) with the full profile assumed adiabatic via Eq. 4.
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Agreed-Upon Approach: Hybrid Two-Stage Strategy
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Stage 1 \'97 Direct Retrieval Network (build first, sufficient for a strong paper):
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Train a supervised neural network on ~500k libRadtran simulations
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Input: reflectances R(\uc0\u955 ) + geometry (SZA, VZA, \u966 , wind speed)
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Output: r_e at N=10 vertical levels + \uc0\u964 _c, as 
\f2\b separate named outputs
\f4\b0  (not a raw vector)
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Add physics-based penalties to the loss: monotonicity (replaces r_bot < r_top), adiabatic shape (soft version of Eq. 4), smoothness
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Loss = L_supervised + \uc0\u955 \u8321 \'b7L_monotonicity + \u955 \u8322 \'b7L_adiabatic + \u955 \u8323 \'b7L_smoothness
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Stage 2 \'97 Add Forward Model Emulator (if time permits, ~1-2 weeks extra):
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Train a separate NN to emulate libRadtran: (profile, \uc0\u964 _c, geometry) \u8594  predicted R(\u955 )
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 Freeze emulator, plug into training loop as an additional loss term: L_data = ||\uc0\u82 \u770 (\u955 ) - R_observed(\u955 )||\'b2
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 The retrieval network from Stage 1 is 
\f2\b reused unchanged
\f4\b0  \'97 the emulator is an add-on
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 This makes it a true PINN because the forward model (radiative transfer) is embedded in the training loop
\f3\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f2\b Key Design Decision: Output Structure
\f3\b0\fs24 \

\f1\fs18\fsmilli9333 \'95
\f4 The retrieval network's forward method returns a dictionary with keys 'profile', 'tau_c', 'profile_normalized', 'tau_normalized'. This clean separation enables the Stage 2 emulator to be connected directly to the retrieval network output without any restructuring.
\f3\fs24 \

